quest number	question statement	Option A	Option B	Option C	Option D	Option E	Answer	justifications
1	You are managing a software development project that is 60% complete. at a sprint review, the marketing team mentions that the new Chief Marketing Officer (CMO) who started last month has expressed concerns the user interface design and wants to be involved in upcoming decisions. What should the project manager do FIRST?	Inform the marketing team that the design was already approved by stakeholders during initiation and cannot be changed without a formal change request.	Schedule a meeting with the new CMO to understand their concerns and update the stakeholder register to include them.	Ask the marketing team to have the new CMO submit their feedback through the existing project communication channels.	Continue with the current sprint as planned and address the CMO's concerns during the next project phase.		B	PMBOK 7 highlights the importance of proactively identifying and optimizing risk responses to reduce uncertainty and improve project success. Optimize Risk Responses, pp. 53–54.
2	You are managing. a city park project for a new community center in the process involving city council members, residents, environmental groups, contractors, and the project sponsor. You have been sending weekly email status reports to all stakeholders for the past three months, but email response rates have dropped significantly and several key decisions are being delayed because stakeholders are not providing timely feedback. What is the BEST approach to improve stakeholder engagement?	Increase the frequency of email updates to twice weekly and request read receipts to ensure stakeholders are receiving the information.	Implement a multi-channel communication approach including face-to-face meetings, site visits, online project dashboard, and phone calls based on stakeholder preferences.	Schedule a mandatory monthly meeting for all stakeholders to discuss project status and issues in person.	Create a more detailed email template with and graphics to make the status reports more engaging and informative. _		B	PMBOK 7 focuses on delivering business value and aligning project decisions with organizational and stakeholder benefits. Focus on Value, pp. 34–36.
3	During a project status meeting, you notice that the Marketing Director Who is usually very engaged and talkative, has been unusually quiet and appears frustrated. When you present the timeline for the marketing campaign launch, she briefly responds Fine, whatever works without her typical detailed questions or suggestions. What should you do NEXT?	Continue with your planned work since she said that the timeline was acceptable and you have urgent deliverables to complete.:	Send a follow-up email asking if there are any concerns about the timeline that weren't addressed.	Reach out privately to the Marketing Director to check if everything is okay and understand if there are any underlying concerns.	Schedule another meeting with all stakeholders to revisit the timeline discussion and ensure everyone is truly aligned. a		C	PMBOK 7 stresses building quality into processes and deliverables rather than relying only on inspections after completion. Build Quality into Processes and Deliverables, pp. 47–49.
4	You are managing a project to implement a new customer relationship management (CRM) system for the sales department. During a requirements gathering session, you learn that the new CRM will automatically generate reports that the Finance team uses for commission calculations, and it will integrate with the Customer Service system that tracks warranty claims. What should you do regarding the Finance and Customer Service teams?	Keep them off the stakeholder register since they won't directly use the CRM stem, but ensure the integration requirements are documented in the project scope.	Add both teams to the’stakeholder register and include them in project communications, even though their involvement is indirect.	Contact the Finance and Customer Service teams only if integration issues arise during implementation to avoid unnecessary complexity.	Ask the Sales Director to coordinate with Finance and Customer Service teams on your behalf since they understand the business relationships better. a		B	PMBOK 7 emphasizes leadership behaviors, team empowerment, and decision-making to guide projects effectively. Demonstrate Leadership Behaviors, pp. 40–43.
5	You are managing a website redesign project that is 75% complete and on track to finish on time and within budget. The client calls you with a request to add a new chatbot feature that they saw on a competitor's website, which would require significant additional work and potentially delay the launch by 3-4 weeks. What should you do?	Meet with the client to understand the business value and urgency of the chatbot feature, then analyze the full impact on scope, schedule, cost, and quality before making any decisions.	Inform the client that adding new features at this stage would cause significant delays and cost overruns, and suggest they consider it for a future phase.	Ask the development team to provide a detailed estimate for the chatbot feature so you can present the client with accurate cost and schedule impacts.	Explain to the client that the project scope was already approved and any changes would require going through the formal change control process. |		A	PMBOK 7 recommends tailoring project approaches, methods, and practices according to project context and environment. Tailor Based on Context, pp. 44–46.
6	A project manager is leading an agile software development project when the product owner requests to add a new feature that would enhance user security. The feature was not in the original requirements and would require significant development effort. The team is currently in the middle of a two-week sprint with committed deliverables. What should the project manager do?	Submit the new feature through the formal change control process for approval	Work with the product owner to add the security feature to the product backlog for prioritization in future sprint planning	Immediately incorporate the feature into the current sprint to address security concerns	Reject the request since it wasn't part of the original project scope		B	PMBOK 7 emphasizes systems thinking and coordination across interconnected project components and stakeholders. Recognize, Evaluate, and Respond to System Interactions, pp. 37–39.
7	During your weekly status meeting, the project sponsor mentions that due to new regulatory requirements, the project timeline needs to be accelerated by one month to meet a compliance deadline. The sponsor states, "This is critical for the business and needs to happen. What should the project manager do?	Begin working with the team and develop a compressed schedule that meets the sponsor's requirements.	Ask the sponsor to submit a formal change request detailing the regulatory requirements and timeline changes before proceeding with any schedule analysis. Analyze the current schedule to identify opportunities for compression and present options to the sponsor for their decision		Schedule a follow-up meeting with the sponsor and key stakeholders to discuss the impact of accelerating the timeline. —		B	PMBOK 7 highlights adaptability and resiliency to respond effectively to change and evolving project conditions. Embrace Adaptability and Resiliency, pp. 55–57.
8	You receive a change request from the marketing team to add a social media integration feature to your mobile app project. The request seems straightforward and your lead developer mentions it would be easy to add and estimates about 2 days of work. What should you do?	Approve the change request immediately since it's low-risk and the team has done similar work before.	Ask the marketing team to wait until the next change control board meeting to maintain proper governance.	Conduct a thorough impact assessment of the change request on scope, schedule, cost, quality, and risk before making any decisions.	Since it's urgent and seems small - implement the feature now and document the change retroactively. ==		C	PMBOK 7 explains that effective planning aligns project activities, resources, metrics, and communication with intended outcomes. Planning Performance Domain, pp. 51–68.
9	Your data migration project is scheduled to begin the database transfer this weekend when you discover on Friday afternoon that the backup verification process failed and the backup files are corrupted. The business has already announced the system downtime to users, vendors have been scheduled, and the migration team is standing by. What should you do?	Immediately start working on attempted backup solutions as directed while the IT Director develops the overall strategy.	Postpone the migration until a complete backup and recovery plan can be developed and tested.	Call an emergency planning session to develop a comprehensive approach for addressing the backup issue before taking any corrective actions.	Begin the migration as scheduled but implement additional monitoring and rollback procedures to mitigate the backup risk.		C	PMBOK 7 focuses on delivering usable outcomes and benefits that create value for stakeholders and organizations. Delivery Performance Domain, pp. 80–92.
11	You are managing an e-commerce platform project with several critical issues that need immediate attention, but you Only have resources to address only this week: a security vulnerability that could potentially expose consumer data, a performance issue and slow checkout times that's reducing sales, and a cosmetic bug that the CEO noticed and specifically asked to be fixed quickly. The development team is waiting for your prioritization decision. _ Which issue should you address FIRST?	Fix the security vulnerability to prevent potential breaches and protect customer information, even though it hasn't been exploited yet	Resolve the performance issue since it's actively impacting customer experience and business revenue right now.	Address the cosmetic bug first since the CEO specifically requested it and maintaining executive support is crucial for project success.	Split the team's time among all three issues to make progress on each one rather than fully completing just one. a		A	PMBOK 7 emphasizes active stakeholder engagement, communication, and collaboration to achieve successful project outcomes. Effectively Engage with Stakeholders, pp. 31–33.
12	During your weekly team meeting, a heated argument breaks out between the lead developer and the QA manager about testing timelines. The developer insists that QA is being unreasonable by demanding too much time for testing, while the QA manager argues that the developer is rushing code and creating quality problems. What should you do FIRST?	Stop the argument and remind both team members about professional behavior expectations in meetings.	Schedule separate one-on-one meetings with each team member to understand their underlying concerns and perspectives before attempting resolution.	Implement a new process that allocates specific time for development and testing phases to prevent future scheduling conflicts.	Facilitate a discussion between both team members to find a compromise on the testing timeline that works for everyone. _		B	PMBOK 7 highlights the importance of proactively identifying and optimizing risk responses to reduce uncertainty and improve project success. Optimize Risk Responses, pp. 53–54.
13	During a new software project, a team member discovers a bug in code that was written a few weeks ago. This will cause a major delay if not fixed right away and the team member is uncertain of how to fix it. What should the project manager do first? >	Add this coding error to the issue log and assign an owner.	Add this risk to the risk register and work with the team to fix the code.	Assign a senior coder to fix the coding error. D) Facilitate a discussion between both team members to fix the coding error.			A	PMBOK 7 focuses on delivering business value and aligning project decisions with organizational and stakeholder benefits. Focus on Value, pp. 34–36.
14	You are managing your first healthcare IT project involving HIPAA compliance requirements when a complex technical issue emerges regarding data encryption standards. You've researched online and found conflicting information about the specific requirements, and your team is waiting for guidance with a decision needed by tomorrow. What should you do?	Make the best deci un based on your research and move forward, adjusting later if needed to show decisive leader	Escalate the decision to your project sponsor since compliance issues are above your authority level.	Call a team brainstorming session to collectively research the encryption requirements and reach a consensus decision.	Consult with the company's HIPAA compliance officer, review lessons learned from previous healthcare projects, and check organizational compliance procedures before deciding.: 7		D	PMBOK 7 stresses building quality into processes and deliverables rather than relying only on inspections after completion. Build Quality into Processes and Deliverables, pp. 47–49.
15	You arrive at work to find an urgent voicemail from a key client stating that they're “extremely disappointed with the latest project deliverable and are considering terminating the contract. The client demands an immediate response, and the project team is asking what's happening as word has spread quickly. What should you do FIRST?	Call the client immediately to apologize for their disappointment and assure them that you will personally resolve whatever issues they have.	Review the deliverable that was submitted, check the acceptance criteria, and gather information about what specifically disappointed the client before responding.	Schedule an emergency meeting with your sponsor to discuss how to respond to the client's concerns and develop a recovery plan.	Contact your project sponsor to inform them of the client's threat and get guidance on how to proceed with contract termination.		B	PMBOK 7 emphasizes leadership behaviors, team empowerment, and decision-making to guide projects effectively. Demonstrate Leadership Behaviors, pp. 40–43.
16	Your mobile app development project is now 50% complete according to your project schedule, but stakeholders are expressing concerns about the project's progress and questioning whether the final product will meet their expectations. The development team has been following agile practices but hasn't yet delivered any working functionality that stakeholders can see or test. What should you do to address stakeholder concerns?	Create detailed status reports showing percentage completion for each feature and present them to stakeholders to demonstrate concrete progress.	Organize a demonstration session where the development team can show stakeholders the working components and core functionality developed so far.	Schedule weekly stakeholder meetings to provide verbal updates on development progress and address their concerns through communication,	Reassure stakeholders that the project is on track according to the schedule and ask them to trust the process until the next milestone. _		C	PMBOK 7 recommends tailoring project approaches, methods, and practices according to project context and environment. Tailor Based on Context, pp. 44–46.
17	Your project team has been experiencing low morale due to unclear role responsibilities and frequent miscommunications between the development and testing teams. Team members have been coming to you with complaints about each other, productivity has declined, and you can see tension during team meetings. Your project sponsor mentioned during the last status meeting that they've heard some concerns about team dynamics, What should you do?	Ask your project sponsor to step in and clarify roles and expectations since they have more authority with the team members.	Facilitate team meetings to clarify roles, establish communication protocols, and address the interpersonal issues directly as the project manager.	Request that your sponsor to bring in an HR representative to mediate the team conflicts and establish better working relationships.	Escalate the team dynamics issue to senior leadership and ask for guidance on how to improve morale and productivity. 		B	PMBOK 7 emphasizes systems thinking and coordination across interconnected project components and stakeholders. Recognize, Evaluate, and Respond to System Interactions, pp. 37–39.
18	Your development team has been struggling with a complex technical challenge for the past week, and team morale is low. You notice that the junior developers seem hesitant to speak up during technical discussions, and one team member mentions that they feel out of their league” with the current requirements. What should you do? Take charge of the technical challenge yourself by researching solutions and providing specific direction to each team member on how to implement your findings.		Bring in a senior consultant to solve the technical problem quickly and show the team the correct approach for future similar challenges.	Organize pair programming sessions between senior and junior developers, schedule individual coaching conversations to understand each person's concerns, and celebrate small technical wins along the way.	Reassign the complex work to only the senior developers while giving the junior developers simpler tasks that match their current level.		C	PMBOK 7 highlights adaptability and resiliency to respond effectively to change and evolving project conditions. Embrace Adaptability and Resiliency, pp. 55–57.
19	Your enterprise software implementation project involves multiple work streams: data migration, business process redesign, user training, and system configuration. Each team is progressing well individually, but you're noticing potential integration issues: timeline conflicts, scope misalignments, and missing requirements dependencies. What should you do FIRST?	Focus on the area that's furthest behind schedule and help that team catch up before addressing the integration issues.	Convene an integration planning session with all work stream leads to identify dependencies, resolve conflicts, and align timelines across all areas,	Delegate the integration issues to each functional team lead and ask them to coordinate directly with each other to resolve conflicts	Escalate the integration challenges to the project sponsor since they involve coordination across multiple departments. 		B	PMBOK 7 explains that effective planning aligns project activities, resources, metrics, and communication with intended outcomes. Planning Performance Domain, pp. 51–68.
20	Your project has received approval to proceed with the next phase: developing a new inventory management module. You have the high-level requirements and need to create a detailed work breakdown structure for planning and estimation purposes, but your development team won't be available for detailed planning discussions for another week. What should you do?	Wait for the development team to become available and have them create the WBS together, even though it will delay the planning process by a week.	Create a detailed WBS based on your previous experience with similar modules to keep the project moving forward, then review it with the team when they become available.	Assign the WBS creation to the team lead since they have both the technical expertise and familiarity with the current system here.	Create a high-level WBS framework based on your_experience, then have the team provide detailed breakdown of each major component when they're available.		A	PMBOK 7 focuses on delivering usable outcomes and benefits that create value for stakeholders and organizations. Delivery Performance Domain, pp. 80–92.
21	You are developing the project schedule for a website redesign project. Based on your experience with similar projects and discussions with the client, you believe the optimal sequence would be: design mockups first, then content creation, followed by development, and finally testing. What should you do regarding the activity sequencing?	Identify which of these delayed activities are on the critical path and will actually impact the project end date, then prioritize those for immediate attention.	Present your proposed sequence to the team and ask them to provide time estimates for each phase based on your recommended approach.	Share the project requirements with the team and ask them to determine the optimal sequence and timing of activities based on technical expertise.	Create the schedule based on your experience but remain flexible to modify the sequence if the team identifies any technical constraints.		C	PMBOK 7 emphasizes active stakeholder engagement, communication, and collaboration to achieve successful project outcomes. Effectively Engage with Stakeholders, pp. 31–33.
22	Your project team's performance has been declining over the past month. You've noticed that Sarah, usually your most productive developer, seems disengaged and is producing lower quality work, appearing quiet and distracted during team meetings. What should you do FIRST before implementing performance measures?	Implement the performance improvement measures immediately since declining performance affects the entire project and waiting could make things worse.	Schedule a private conversation with Sarah to understand what's affecting her motivation and engagement with the project	Assign Sarah to less critical tasks until her performance improves to minimize project risk while she works through her issues.	Discuss Sarah's performance decline with the team during the next meeting to get collective input on how to support struggling team members. —		B	PMBOK 7 highlights the importance of proactively identifying and optimizing risk responses to reduce uncertainty and improve project success. Optimize Risk Responses, pp. 53–54.
23	During your software implementation project, you discover that a team member has been inflating their time reports, claiming 8 hours of work on days when they were only present for 4-5 hours. This has been going on for about three weeks, and your manager hints that minor timesheet issues” are common. What should you do?	Address the timesheet issue directly with the team member and establish clear expectations going forward, while documenting the conversation and corrective actions.—	Overlook the timesheet discrepancies since the team member is technically competent and the project can't afford delays from personnel changes.	Quietly discuss the situation with other team members to verify the information before taking any action that could impact the project.	Focus on the team member's deliverable quality and productivity rather than time tracking, since results matter more than hours logged. -		A	PMBOK 7 focuses on delivering business value and aligning project decisions with organizational and stakeholder benefits. Focus on Value, pp. 34–36.
24	During a design review meeting, you notice that whenever the senior architect presents ideas, the junior team members remain silent and simply nod in agreement, even when you can see puzzled expressions on their faces. After the meeting, you overhear two junior developers privately expressing concerns about the proposed architecture, What should you do to improve team dynamics?	Schedule individual meetings with junior team members to gather their technical input privately, then present their concerns in future meetings.	Establish ground rules for meetings that encourage questions and alternative viewpoints, and model constructive disagreement by respectfully questioning ideas yourself.	Ask the senior architect to be more open to questions and input from junior team members during design discussions.	Rotate meeting leadership so that junior team members take turns presenting their ideas and leading technical discussions. _		B	PMBOK 7 stresses building quality into processes and deliverables rather than relying only on inspections after completion. Build Quality into Processes and Deliverables, pp. 47–49.
25	Your web development project is progressing well when the marketing director approaches you with an urgent request for your lead developer to quickly create a promotional landing page for an upcoming trade show. The lead developer is already working at full capacity on critical project features, but they're the only team member with the specific skills needed for this promotional work. What should you do?	Ask the lead developer to take on the promotional landing page since it's only a few hours and could benefit the company. 	Negotiate with the marketing director to delay the promotional landing page until after the current sprint is completed.	Have the lead developer train a team member to handle the promotional work so the expertise can be distributed across the.	Discuss the request with the lead developer to understand the capacity impact, then decline if it would compromise their focus on primary project responsibilities.		D	PMBOK 7 emphasizes leadership behaviors, team empowerment, and decision-making to guide projects effectively. Demonstrate Leadership Behaviors, pp. 40–43.
26	A project manager is leading a data analytics platform implementation when the team realizes they lack sufficient expertise in the new analytics tools. Three team members have basic knowledge, one has intermediate expertise and one has advanced expertise. The team needs to develop these skills quickly to maintain project momentum. What should the project manager do?	Enroll the entire team in formal training colleges to ensure consistent skill levels	Organize peer learning sessions where team members teach and learn from each other	Hire additional team members with the required analytics expertise	Outsource the analytics components to an external vendor with proven capabilities		B	PMBOK 7 recommends tailoring project approaches, methods, and practices according to project context and environment. Tailor Based on Context, pp. 44–46.
27	A project manager notices that one team member consistently arrives late to meetings, interrupts others during discussions, and submits deliverables past agreed deadlines. This behavior is affecting team morale and project progress. Other team members have started making comments about the individual's performance during team meetings, and some have approached the project manager requesting action. What should the project manager do first?	Address the performance issues with the individual in a private one-on-one meeting	Discuss the team member's behavior during the next team meeting to ensure transparency	Document the performance issues and escalate to human resources for disciplinary action	Reassign the problematic team member to tasks that require less collaboration		A	PMBOK 7 emphasizes systems thinking and coordination across interconnected project components and stakeholders. Recognize, Evaluate, and Respond to System Interactions, pp. 37–39.
28	Your agile development team is starting the next sprint planning session, but the product owner has been traveling and hasn't had time to properly document the user stories for the upcoming features. The development team is eager to start working and has already identified several features from previous discussions that they believe are high priority. What should you do?	Allow the development team to start working on the features they identified as high priority while the product owner completes the documentation in parallel.	Have the development team create the initial documentation based on their understanding, then review it with the product Owner when they return.	Postpone sprint planning wait until the product owner can properly document and prioritize the features, even if it causes a time delay.	Work with the product owner to quickly prioritize the most critical features and have them document just those stories needed to start the sprint.		D	PMBOK 7 highlights adaptability and resiliency to respond effectively to change and evolving project conditions. Embrace Adaptability and Resiliency, pp. 55–57.
29	Your agile development project has team members distributed across three different office locations in New York City. The team has been working remotely using video calls and collaboration tools, but you've noticed increasing communication delays and coordination each sprint. What should you do to enhance collaboration?	Invest in better video conferencing technology and collaboration tools to improve the remote working experience.	Arrange for team members from different locations to travel and work together in the same location for the most critical project phases.	Establish more frequent check-in meetings and structured communication protocols to improve coordination across locations.	Reorganize the work to minimize dependencies between different locations and allow each site to work more independently.		B	PMBOK 7 explains that effective planning aligns project activities, resources, metrics, and communication with intended outcomes. Planning Performance Domain, pp. 51–68.
30	Your organization has decided to transition from traditional waterfall project management to agile methodologies across all development teams, The CTO wants to implement agile practices organization-wide immediately to get the benefits as quickly as possible and has scheduled agile training for all teams next month. What should you recommend for implementing this methodology change?	Support the CTO's plan to implement agile across all teams simultaneously after the training to ensure consistent adoption and quick benefits realization.	Select 1-2 teams for an initial agile pilot project, gather lessons learned, refine the approach, then gradually roll out to additional teams based on pilot results.	Implement agile only for new projects while allowing current projects to finish using traditional methods, then transition all teams once current work is completed.	Divide the teams into two groups and implement agile in phases: first group starts immediately after training, second group starts 3 months later. a		B	PMBOK 7 focuses on delivering usable outcomes and benefits that create value for stakeholders and organizations. Delivery Performance Domain, pp. 80–92.
31	Your agile team has been developing a mobile app for the past three sprints. The customer was very engaged during the initial requirements gathering but has been increasingly difficult to reach for feedback sessions, missing the last two sprint reviews and saying they're too busy to attend regular meetings.” What should you do?	Insist on regular customer feedback sessions and adjust the sprint schedule if necessary to accommodate the customer's availability, even if it slows down development velocity.	Continue development based on the original requirements since the customer has expressed trust in the team, and schedule a comprehensive review before the final release.	Have the product owner make customer value decisions based on their business knowledge to maintain development momentum while the customer is unavailable.	Pause development until the customer becomes available for regular feedback sessions, since agile cannot function effectively without ongoing customer input. _		A	PMBOK 7 emphasizes active stakeholder engagement, communication, and collaboration to achieve successful project outcomes. Effectively Engage with Stakeholders, pp. 31–33.
32	Your team is starting development on a new e-commerce platform. During the initial planning meetings, stakeholders have focused heavily on functional requirements but have provided minimal guidance on quality standards, responding that we'll figure that out as we go and just make it work well. What should you do before development begins?	Proceed with development using industry standard quality practices, since the team has experience and stakeholders trust their judgment on quality matters.	Begin development of core features while scheduling quality requirement discussions for later sprints when stakeholders can see working software and provide more specific feedback.	Research similar e-commerce platforms to identify typical quality standards and use those as default requirements until stakeholders provide specific guidance.	Facilitate sessions with stakeholders to define specific quality requirements for performance, security, usability, and reliability before any development work begins.:		D	PMBOK 7 highlights the importance of proactively identifying and optimizing risk responses to reduce uncertainty and improve project success. Optimize Risk Responses, pp. 53–54.
33	Your team has completed the first major deliverable of your web application project: a fully functional user authentication system. The stem meets all technical specifications and passes all automated tests, but the customer has been traveling and won't be available for validation testing until the-end of the next phase. What should you do?	Deploy the authentication ep’ to production since it meets all technical requirements and has passed internal quality checks, but customer validation afterward.	Continue with the next development phase while waiting for customer validation, since the technical team is confident the deliverable meets requirements.	Wait for the customer to return and validate the authentication system before proceeding with deployment or the next development phase.	Present the authentication system to a customer representative or proxy who can provide preliminary validation until the primary customer is available. a		D	PMBOK 7 focuses on delivering business value and aligning project decisions with organizational and stakeholder benefits. Focus on Value, pp. 34–36.
34	Your cross-functional team needs to brainstorm solutions for a complex integration challenge that affects multiple system components. The team includes developers, business analysts, subject matter experts, and stakeholders with varying technical backgrounds who. all need to contribute ideas and understand the proposed solutions: What should you do to facilitate effective collaboration?	Schedule a series of detailed technical meetings where experts can present comprehensive solution architectures using diagrams.	Set up a digital collaboration platform where team members can contribute ideas asynchronously through structured templates and voting mechanisms. —	Create a shared online workspace with editing capabilities where all stakeholders can simultaneously contribute to solution that	Organize a workshop where everyone Can sketch ideas on whiteboards and collaboratively build solutions using sticky note diagrams.		D	PMBOK 7 stresses building quality into processes and deliverables rather than relying only on inspections after completion. Build Quality into Processes and Deliverables, pp. 47–49.
35	Your team needs to provide time estimates for developing a new customer portal with several integrated modules. The project sponsor is asking for accurate estimates to support budget planning and resource allocation decisions. Which estimation approach should you use?	Use your experience from a similar a project and apply scaling factors, since historical data provides reliable baseline estimates much faster than detailed breakdown.	Have technical leads provide high-level estimates for each module based on their expertise, since they understand the technical complexity better than individual developers.	Get detailed task-level estimates from the developers who will perform the work, then aggregate these estimates to create the overall project timeline.	Combine approaches by using historical data for the initial estimate, then having technical leads validate and adjust based on specific project differences, —		C	PMBOK 7 emphasizes leadership behaviors, team empowerment, and decision-making to guide projects effectively. Demonstrate Leadership Behaviors, pp. 40–43.
36	You are starting a new cloud migration project for your organization's legacy systems. The project sponsor is eager to begin the migration work immediately and has expressed concerns that spending too much time on planning activities might delay the benefits realization. What should you do FIRST?	Conduct comprehensive risk identification sessions with all stakeholders before beginning any migration work, documenting potential technical, business, and organizational risks.	Begin the migration with less critical systems first to gain experience and identify risks through hands-on learning during the initial phases.	Start with technical migration since the team is experienced, while conducting risk identification activities in parallel during the first few weeks.	Focus on technical risks only since those are most likely to impact a cloud migration project, leaving business and organizational risk assessment for later phases. —-		A	PMBOK 7 recommends tailoring project approaches, methods, and practices according to project context and environment. Tailor Based on Context, pp. 44–46.
37	Your software development project is progressing well when you receive unexpected news: a major competitor has just announced they're discontinuing their similar product, creating a significant market opportunity for your project. Additionally, a key technology vendor has offered you early access to their new API that could enhance your product capabilities beyond the original scope. What should you dofiisee	Quickly modify the project scope to incorporate the new API features and accelerated market positioning. 2. B) Schedule an emergency stakeholder meeting to discuss how to pivot the project strategy to ‘capture maximum benefit. } C) Document these developments in your risk register and develop specific response strategies for each opportunity.		Document these developments in your risk register and develop specific response strategies for	Begin implementation planning the API integration while your team researches the competitive landscape changes. 		C	PMBOK 7 emphasizes systems thinking and coordination across interconnected project components and stakeholders. Recognize, Evaluate, and Respond to System Interactions, pp. 37–39.
38	You're negotiating a contract with a software development vendor for a critical project component. Your procurement team has drafted a contract that includes steep penalty clauses for any delays, requires the vendor to accept unlimited liability for any issues, and provides limited payment milestones. What should you recommend regarding this contract structure?	Proceed with the contract as drafted since it maximizes protection for your organization and the vendor has already agreed to the terms. 	Modify the contract to create more balanced risk sharing, reasonable payment terms, and incentives that benefit both parties for successful delivery.	Add additional penalty clauses to ensure vendor performance while maintaining the current favorable terms for your organization	Accept the current terms but add bonus incentives for early delivery to provide some upside for the vendor while keeping the protective clauses.		B	PMBOK 7 highlights adaptability and resiliency to respond effectively to change and evolving project conditions. Embrace Adaptability and Resiliency, pp. 55–57.
39	Your agile development project is halfway through when your team discovers that the initial API integration approach isn't working as expected, requiring a complete technical pivot that cost two weeks but ultimately led to a much better solution. Additionally, you learned that conducting user testing sessions every three sprints instead of every sprint actually provides better feedback quality. What should you do regarding these discoveries? '	Wait until the project retrospective at the end to document all lessons learned comprehensively, ensuring you capture the complete picture of what worked and what didn't.	Document these learnings immediately in the lessons learned register so they can benefit the current project and future projects, even if it takes time from current sprint work.	Share these insights informally with other project teams through casual conversations and team meetings, since formal documentation can be done later.	Focus on completing the current deliverables first, then schedule dedicated time after the next release to properly document and analyze lessons.		B	PMBOK 7 explains that effective planning aligns project activities, resources, metrics, and communication with intended outcomes. Planning Performance Domain, pp. 51–68.
40	Your mobile app development project has been cancelled due to strategic changes in the organization, The executive team wants to immediately reassign all project resources to a new priority initiative that starts next week, instructing you to Wrap things up since there's no deliverable to complete. What should you do? 	Immediately transition the team to the project as requested, handling the administrative cleanup tasks yourself over the next few 	Request additional time to properly close out all vendor contracts, collect equipment, organize documentation, and conduct final financial reconciliation before team reassignment.	Assign one team member to handle the closure activities while moving the rest of the team to the new project to balance both priorities.	Document the current project status and Outstanding items, then hand over closure responsibilities to the operations team transitioning the project team immediately. .		B	PMBOK 7 focuses on delivering usable outcomes and benefits that create value for stakeholders and organizations. Delivery Performance Domain, pp. 80–92.
41	Your e-commerce platform project is three months into development when you notice the team has become highly focused on technical implementation details and sprint deliverables. Team members seem to have lost sight of the bigger picture: Creating seamless customer experience that will revolutionize how users interact with the company's products. What should you do to address this situation?	Continue letting the team focus on technical excellence since they're making good progress on deliverables and the vision will become clear once they see the finished product.	Bring in the product owner to realign the team with business requirements and ensure technical decisions support user experience goals.	Create detailed user stories that explicitly reflect each technical task to specific customer experience outcomes. ae	Schedule regular sessions to discuss and reinforce how the current technical work connects to the overall vision of revolutionizing customer experience.		D	PMBOK 7 emphasizes active stakeholder engagement, communication, and collaboration to achieve successful project outcomes. Effectively Engage with Stakeholders, pp. 31–33.
